<paragraph id="8BB236DEFFC6FFADFF09F979EF7BAFC4" blockId="15.[151,1437,1701,2015]" pageId="15" pageNumber="520">
<emphasis id="B979EACCFFC6FFADFF09F979EA9DAF1C" bold="true" box="[199,472,1773,1799]" pageId="15" pageNumber="520">Diagnostic characters.</emphasis>
Adult male. AR 1.12. Frontal tubercles large. Tergite IX entirely covered with microtrichia, with double lateral teeth; anal tergite bands V-type, separated, ending well anterior to anal point base (
<figureCitation id="13362A5BFFC6FFADFF6EF8A1EA58AF54" box="[160,285,1845,1871]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanytarsus hastatus Sublette et Sasa, 1994, male. A, B: hypopygium in dorsal (A) and ventral aspect (B); C: arrangement of anal point, superior volsella and digitus; D: median volsellae; (C–D magnified ca. 2–3 times relative to A and B)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6504158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6504158/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="520">Fig. 7A, B</figureCitation>
). Anal point robust, lanceolate, pointed, with pair of well-developed crests, area between crests with numerous small spinulae; superior volsella more or less circular at base, with concave median margin and well projecting posteromedian corner, field of microtrichia on dorsal surface absent; digitus long and pointed, fingerlike, extending well beyond margin of superior volsella (
<figureCitation id="13362A5BFFC6FFADFCD8F835E82BAFA0" box="[790,878,1953,1979]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanytarsus hastatus Sublette et Sasa, 1994, male. A, B: hypopygium in dorsal (A) and ventral aspect (B); C: arrangement of anal point, superior volsella and digitus; D: median volsellae; (C–D magnified ca. 2–3 times relative to A and B)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6504158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6504158/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="520">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
). Median volsella with foliate lamellae (
<figureCitation id="13362A5BFFC6FFADFAFBF835EECAAFA0" box="[1333,1423,1953,1979]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetId="figure-20@16.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanytarsus hastatus Sublette et Sasa, 1994, male. A, B: hypopygium in dorsal (A) and ventral aspect (B); C: arrangement of anal point, superior volsella and digitus; D: median volsellae; (C–D magnified ca. 2–3 times relative to A and B)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6504158" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6504158/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="520">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
). Inferior volsella slightly curved, with swollen round apex directed posteromedially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
