<subSubSection id="C3176555FFD8FFB3FF09FF02EAACA906" pageId="17" pageNumber="522" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB236DEFFD8FFB3FF09FF02EAACA906" blockId="17.[151,1436,150,285]" pageId="17" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis id="B979EACCFFD8FFB3FF09FF02E91EA8AA" bold="true" box="[199,603,150,177]" pageId="17" pageNumber="522">Distribution and ecological notes.</emphasis>
The present record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D4D5DFFD8FFB3FCAFFF03EF04A8AA" authorityName="Sublette et Sasa" authorityYear="1994" box="[865,1089,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Tanytarsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="522" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hastatus">
<emphasis id="B979EACCFFD8FFB3FCAFFF03EF04A8AA" box="[865,1089,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="522">Tanytarsus hastatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry id="F31A764EFFD8FFB3FBA6FF03EF93A8AA" box="[1128,1238,151,177]" name="Colombia" pageId="17" pageNumber="522">Colombia</collectingCountry>
is the first in the Andean region and its highest known location above sea level. As a result, the vertical distribution gradient known for 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D4D5DFFD8FFB3FF71FF4BEA7CA8E2" authorityName="Sublette et Sasa" authorityYear="1994" box="[191,313,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Chironomidae" genus="Tanytarsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="522" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hastatus">
<emphasis id="B979EACCFFD8FFB3FF71FF4BEA7CA8E2" box="[191,313,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="522">T. hastatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ranges from 0 to an altitude of 1800 meters. The specimens were collected in an urban area, on the seventh floor of an aparthotel.
